{"title_page": "Kasauli", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Kasauli\n| other_name                      = Kussowlie\n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                = [[Cantonment]]\n| image_skyline                   = Kasauli Circuit House.jpg|\n| image_alt                       = \n| imagesize                       = 300px\n| image_caption                   = Kasauli Circuit House, British period heritage building\n| pushpin_map                     = India Himachal Pradesh#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Himachal Pradesh, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|30.9|N|76.96|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Himachal Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Solan district|Solan]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 1800\n| population_total                = \n| population_as_of                = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code                     = 173204\n| registration_plate              = [[List of RTO districts in India#HP.E2.80.94Himachal_Pradesh|HP]]-\n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Kasauli''' is a [[cantonment]] and town, located in [[Solan district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Himachal Pradesh]]. The cantonment was established by the [[British Raj]] in 1842 as a Colonial [[hill station]],<ref name=Tribune>Sharma, Ambika; [http://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010302/art-trib.htm#1 \"Architecture of Kasauli churches\"]; ''[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]'', Online edition, 2 March 2001. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref> 77&nbsp;km from [[Shimla]], 65&nbsp;km from [[Chandigarh]], and 94&nbsp;km from [[Ambala Cantt]] ([[Haryana]]), an important railway junction of North India.\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2011 India [[census]], Kasauli had a population of 4,994. The male population constituted 56% of the population while the female population was 44%. Kasauli had an average literacy rate of 80%, higher than the then national average of 75.5%; male literacy was 84%, and female 76%. 10% of the population was under 6 years of age.\n\n==Climate==\n[[File:Kasauli, Himachal Pradesh.jpg|upright=1|thumb|Kasauli on a winter afternoon.]]\n\nKasauli has a moderate climate. Winter temperature is approximately 2 degrees Celsius, the summer temperatures rarely exceeds 32 degrees Celsius or more. The general wind direction is south-west to north-east. Total rainfall for the year is 1020 millimetres, with humidity at 90% in September and 28% in April. Sometimes snowfall is also there during early January and in winters are chilly, there are a couple of frosty nights. Minimum temperature recorded in Kasuli was -6\u00b0 Celsius.\n\n== Landmarks ==\n\n=== Central Research Institute ===\nThe Central Research Institute (CRI), originally the Pasteur Institute of India, was established at Kasauli in 1904 under its first director [[Sir David Semple]], as an institute working in the fields of immunology and virological research.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1038/146023a0|title = Pasteur Institute of India, Kasauli|journal = Nature|volume = 146|issue = 3688|pages = 23|year = 1940|bibcode = 1940Natur.146Q..23.|doi-access = free}}</ref>\n\nThe CRI works as a [[World Health Organization]] \u2018Collaborating Centre\u2019, and as an immuno-biological laboratory producing vaccines for [[measles]] and [[polio]], and the [[DPT vaccine|DTP]] group of vaccines. It also provides a [[Master of Science]] programme in Microbiology.\n\n===Baptist Church===\nKasauli [[Baptists|Baptist Church]] is a 1923 brick and wood building, situated close to the Sadar Bazzar. According to ''[[The Indian Express]]'' it is \"considered a unique example of colonial architecture of the British era\". In 2008 the church was damaged by a fire which destroyed all the internal furnishings.<ref name=\"ChurchesHimachalPradesh\" /><ref name=\"Kashyap\">Kashyap, Arvind; [http://www.indianexpress.com/news/kasauli-church-pastor-suspects-arson/385387/ \"Kasauli church pastor suspects arson\"]; ''[[The Indian Express]]'', 14 Nov 2008. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref><ref>[http://news.oneindia.in/2008/11/12/fire-breaks-out-in-kasauli-church-pastor-seeks-probe-1226497015.html \"Fire breaks out in Kasauli Church, Pastor seeks probe\"]; ''[[Oneindia.in]]'', 12 November 2008. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref>\n\n===Christ Church===\n[[File:Christ Church, Kasauli ,Solan ,Himachal Pardesh.jpg|alt=he church in itself is very beautiful and artistic. Attracts a lot of visitors.|thumb|picturesque structure ]]\nChrist Church was previously an [[Anglican]] church, inaugurated on 24 July 1853.<ref name=ChurchesHimachalPradesh>[http://himachal-pradesh-tourism.com/himachal-pradesh-churches.html \"Churches in Himachal Pradesh\"]; Himachal-pradesh-tourism.com. Retrieved 27 June 2012</ref>\n\nChrist church Kasauli came into existence in 1844 when Dr. Daniel Wilson (the great Metropolitan Bishop of Calcutta) appointed Rev MJ Jennings a chaplain to the new station Kasauli for the 1st time. Who started worship services in a barrack as there was no church building. \nAt the end of October 1844 Dr. Wilson, the Bishop of Calcutta paid his 1st visitation of Kasauli and on 26th of that month laid the foundation stone of future Christ Church. On 24th July 1853 the shed of the church was completed and on that day the church was used for the worship services for 1st time. \nIn 1880s the church tower was raised and the public clock was placed on it in the leadership of Rev J.B. Brunesson by importing the same from W.H. Bailey & Co of Manchester, England. The total cost of this was Rs. 2612 and 11 annas towards which Rs. 1250 was given by Government and the balance raised by public subscription. After remaining in hibernation for many decades this Tower Clock, In 2015 the clock starts ticking again with the wonderful efforts of Good Samaritan from Chandigarh and the Local EME workshop. Clock still works on Mechanical gears and now in Limca book of Records for being the oldest working Tower Turret Clock in India. [https://amolak.in/web/in-kasauli-the-church-clock-is-ticking-again/ Link for the restoration story]\n\n\n[[File:CHRIST CHURCH, KASAULI.JPG|270px|thumb|Christ Church, Kasauli]]\n\nSince 1970 it has been under the auspices of the [[Church of North India]] (CNI) in the diocese of [[Amritsar]].<ref name=KasauliChurches>[http://www.kasauliresort.com/kasauli_church.html Kasauli Churches] Kasauliresort.com. Retrieved 9 May 2011</ref> The church contains Spanish and Italian imported [[stained glass]] windows depicting [[Jesus|Christ]], [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Mary]], [[Barnabas|Saint Barnabas]] and [[Francis of Assisi|Saint Francis]].<ref name=Tribune/>\n\n===Circuit house===\n===Shri Guru Singh Sabha Kasauli was founded in 1865 by a civil and military contractor Bhai Kahan Singh of Jaswal clan from Hoshiarpur area. This heritage sikh temple is the oldest in this region. This is patronised by the community from neighbouring areas. Foundation day is celebrated in the month of September every year.===\n===Krishna Bhavan Mandir===\n'''Krishna Bhawan Mandir''', a [[Hindus|Hindu]] shrine, is located in the middle of the town. Dedicated to [[Krishna|Lord Krishna]], the temple exhibits blend of European and Indian architecture. The mandir is situated in the town and attracts tourists throughout the year. Krishna Bhawan Mandir was built in the year 1926 during the British regime. Imperial rulers, specialists of grand buildings came together with local craftsmen to construct this beautiful shrine. Keeping in mind the principles of Vastu Shastra, the designers and craftsmen built this religious monument.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n===Kasauli Brewery===\nThe [[Kasauli Brewery]] and distillery, founded in the 1820s{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} before the establishment of the Kasauli cantonment, is the oldest extant distillery for [[scotch whisky]] in Asia.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}} The Kasauli brewery is also known as [[Mohan Meakin]].{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n===Kasauli Club===\nThe Kasauli Club was established by civilians and service personnel in 1880, as the Kasauli Reading and Assembly Rooms. It gained its present name in 1898 when a limited liability company and constitution were established; its first director was Sir David Semple of Kasauli's Pasteur Institute. At the time the Club was for the exclusive use of the British Raj, and held social meetings, [[Tea dance|tea and dinner dances]], and [[Festival|galas]]. In 1915 regimental officers at [[Dagshai]], Solan and Subathu could be admitted as honorary members. At [[Indian Independence Act 1947|Independence]] in 1947, plans to sell the then loss-making Club failed.<ref name=Tribune2>Sharma, Ambika; [http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20050529/spectrum/main3.htm \"An exclusive retreat in the hills\"]; ''The Tribune'', Online edition, 29 May 2005. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref>\n\nThe Club was originally constructed of wood and plaster, and was typical of hill architecture. In 2001, after a 2000 restoration, it was destroyed by fire, losing \"elegant, old-world furniture, [and] precious and rare books\". By 2005 it had been redesigned and rebuilt in stone, and plans were put forward for a new attached gymnasium.<ref name=Tribune2/>\n\nIt is currently located within Indian Army premises and managed by a regular Indian Army Officer as Club Secretary, aided by civilian staff.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nIn April 2012 the Kasauli Club hosted a two-day [[Rhythm and Blues]] Festival as a [[benefit concert]] for ill children.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-09/india/31312385_1_army-band-army-jawan-music-lovers \"Rhythm and Blues festival ends with resolve to work for a cause\"], ''[[The Times of India]]'', 9 April 2012. Retrieved 7 July 2012</ref><ref name=Kapoor>Kapoor, Jaskiran; [http://www.indianexpress.com/news/music-in-the-mountains/930231/ \"Music in the Mountains\"]; ''The Indian Express'', 30 March 2012. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref>\n\n===Nahri Temple===\nThe Nahri Temple, devoted to the Goddess Durga and Lord Shiva, is thought to have been constructed around a hundred and fifty years ago. Also known as 'Jantar Mantar' and 'Choo Mantar Mahadev Temple', the temple is renowned for its festive celebration of Dushera and Shivratri. The temple boasts striking idols of the goddess Durga and Lord Shiva placed in the chamber of temple. Near this temple, there is century-old ''bauri'' which still offers sweet potable water. This temple is known to be visited by hundreds of pilgrims each year to present their prayers.\n\n===Hanuman Mandir (Monkey Point)===\n[[File:Fort of Beja Princely State ,Simla Hill States,Himachal Prades,India.jpg|thumb|Palace Fort Beja State]]Monkey Point is situated in the Air Force Station near the Lower Mall region about 4 km from the center of town. According to the Ramayana, when Lord Hanuman was returning from the Himalayas after acquiring the \"Sanjivani Booty\", one of his feet touched the hill; that's why the top of the hill is in the shape of a foot. On clear nights a view of [[Chandigarh]] can be seen from Monkey Point. \n\n===Beja State===\n{{Main article|Beja State}}[[Beja State]] was one of the 18 [[Hill States of India|Simla Hill States]], situated just below Kasauli to the west and bordered by Mahlog, Patiala, Kuthar and the Bharauli tract of Simla District around Sabathu. Beja included 45 villages, over an area of 13 km2 or 5 mi2 with 1,131 subjects.\n\n===Mahlog State===\n{{Main article|Mahlog }}\n[[File:View of Palace and fort of Mahlog State, under Simla Hill States ,Himachal Pradesh,India.jpg|thumb|View of Palace and fort of Mahlog State, under Simla Hill States]]The state of [[Mahlog]] was founded in 1183. Its original rulers were ruling earlier near [[Kalka]] when Mohamad Gauri attacked that area then they shifted to the Mahlog area. Initially 193 villages were in its jurisdiction but later over 300 villages were included. It was the one of the biggest Princely State of Simla Hill States under the British Raj.\n\n==Education==\nEducational institutions in or near Kasauli are the [[Lawrence School Sanawar]], The Pinegrove School, [[St. Mary's Convent School Kasauli|St. Mary's Convent School]], all co-educational, and the school at Kasauli's K.V. Air Force Station. These schools are affiliated with the [[Central Board of Secondary Education]]\nalso \n[[GSSS Kot Beja]] is a government senior secondary school at Kot beja near Kasauli .{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}[[File:Map of Mhlog State under Simla Hill States ,Himachal Pradesh,India.jpg|thumb|left|Map of Mhlog State under Simla Hill States, Himachal Pradesh, India]]\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- Anyone added here should have a Wikipedia article, or inline cites to Independent Verifiable Sources to prove notability and that they were born or spent significant time here - if none forthcoming, the name will be removed. Add in alphabetic order -->\n*[[Sir]] [[Braj Kumar Nehru]], former [[Governor]] of [[Assam]] and [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[Ambassador of India to United States of America|Ambassador of India to the United States]] (1961\u20131968) and [[India House, London|Indian High Commissioner to the United Kingdom]] (1973\u20131977) was a former resident.\n*[[Michael Baines]], English cricketer and British Army officer, born in Kasauli<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27613/27613.html |title=Player profile: Michael Baines |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2019-04-05 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n*[[Frank Blaker]], [[Victoria Cross]] recipient, born in Kasauli<ref>[http://www.victoriacross.org.uk/ggburma.htm \"Known graves of holders of The Victoria Cross - Frank Gerald Blaker\"], Victoriacross.org.uk. Retrieved 6 February 2014</ref>\n*[[Ruskin Bond]] &ndash; [[Anglo-Indian]] author, born in Kasauli\n*[[Tisca Chopra]], Indian film actress, born in Kasauli\n*[[Nathuram Godse]] &ndash; assassin of [[Mahatma Gandhi]], held in a Kasauli barrack during his trial<ref>Walia, Rajan; [http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-17/india/29427534_1_barrack-shimla-kasauli \"Museum planned in complex where Godse was jailed\"], ''The Times of India'', 17 April 2011. Retrieved 7 July 2012</ref>\n*[[Andy Mulligan (rugby union)|Andy Mulligan]] &ndash; [[Ireland national rugby union team|Irish rugby international]], born in Kasauli\n*[[Giles Radice, Baron Radice]] &ndash; resident of Kasauli, 1942&ndash;46<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2004-04-29/chandigarh/28345223_1_kasauli-amazing-memory-sanatorium \"Lord Radice on mission total recall\"], ''The Times of India'', 29 April 2004. Retrieved 7 July 2012</ref>\n*[[Khushwant Singh]] - part-time resident of Kasauli and inspiration for the annual Kushwant Singh Literary Festival hosted in Kasauli since 2012.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/chandigarh/writing-on-the-wall-8/\n| title = Writing on the Wall\n| date = 2013-10-15\n| website = The Indian Express\n| access-date = 2016-02-25\n}}</ref>\n*[https://vidwan.inflibnet.ac.in/profile/16780 Dr Krishan Kumar Tripathi]  - Pioneer Biotechnologist, worked as a scientist in CRI Kasauli.\n\n. Acharya '''Krishan Kant Attri''' (Born in Garkhal-Kasauli) - First Hindu Chaplain To UK Armed Force's. He Got MBE (Member of the Order of the British Empire) From Prince.\n\n. '''Ann Codrington''' (1894\u20131982) British Actress :\nBorn: September 10, 1894 in Kasauli, Solan, Himachal Pradesh, India\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Kasauli}}\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Kasauli}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110709163109/http://himachal.nic.in/welcome.asp Himachal Pradesh website]. Retrieved 8 July 2011\n*[http://www.himachal.nic.in/tcp/DPKASAULI.pdf \"Development plan for Kasauli Planning Area\"], Himachal Pradesh Government. Retrieved 8 July 2011\n*[http://www.tranquilblog.com/2013/07/kasaulitour.html \"Kasauli - My Ride\"], Tranquilblog\n*[http://eragenx.com/2016/07/11/things-to-do-places-visit-kasauli/ \"Places to visit in Kasauli\"], Travel Diary\n\n[[Category:1842 establishments in British India]]\n[[Category:Cantonments of British India]]\n[[Category:Cantonments of India]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Solan district]]\n[[Category:Hill stations in Himachal Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Kasauli\n| other_name                      = Kussowlie\n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                = [[Cantonment]]\n| image_skyline                   = Kasauli Circuit House.jpg|\n| image_alt                       = \n| imagesize                       = 300px\n| image_caption                   = Kasauli Circuit House, British period heritage building\n| pushpin_map                     = India Himachal Pradesh#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Himachal Pradesh, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|30.9|N|76.96|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Himachal Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Solan district|Solan]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 1800\n| population_total                = \n| population_as_of                = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code                     = 173204\n| registration_plate              = [[List of RTO districts in India#HP.E2.80.94Himachal_Pradesh|HP]]-\n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Kasauli''' is a [[cantonment]] and town, located in [[Solan district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Himachal Pradesh]]. The cantonment was established by the [[British Raj]] in 1842 as a Colonial [[hill station]],<ref name=Tribune>Sharma, Ambika; [http://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010302/art-trib.htm#1 \"Architecture of Kasauli churches\"]; ''[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]'', Online edition, 2 March 2001. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref> 77&nbsp;km from [[Shimla]], 65&nbsp;km from [[Chandigarh]], and 94&nbsp;km from [[Ambala Cantt]] ([[Haryana]]), an important railway junction of North India.\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2011 India [[census]], Kasauli had a population of 4,994. The male population constituted 56% of the population while the female population was 44%. Kasauli had an average literacy rate of 80%, higher than the then national average of 75.5%; male literacy was 84%, and female 76%. 10% of the population was under 6 years of age.\n\n==Climate==\n[[File:Kasauli, Himachal Pradesh.jpg|upright=1|thumb|Kasauli on a winter afternoon.]]\n\nKasauli has a moderate climate. Winter temperature is approximately 2 degrees Celsius, the summer temperatures rarely exceeds 32 degrees Celsius or more. The general wind direction is south-west to north-east. Total rainfall for the year is 1020 millimetres, with humidity at 90% in September and 28% in April. Sometimes snowfall is also there during early January and in winters are chilly, there are a couple of frosty nights. Minimum temperature recorded in Kasuli was -6\u00b0 Celsius.\n\n== Landmarks ==\n\n=== Central Research Institute ===\nThe Central Research Institute (CRI), originally the Pasteur Institute of India, was established at Kasauli in 1904 under its first director [[Sir David Semple]], as an institute working in the fields of immunology and virological research.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1038/146023a0|title = Pasteur Institute of India, Kasauli|journal = Nature|volume = 146|issue = 3688|pages = 23|year = 1940|bibcode = 1940Natur.146Q..23.|doi-access = free}}</ref>\n\nThe CRI works as a [[World Health Organization]] \u2018Collaborating Centre\u2019, and as an immuno-biological laboratory producing vaccines for [[measles]] and [[polio]], and the [[DPT vaccine|DTP]] group of vaccines. It also provides a [[Master of Science]] programme in Microbiology.\n\n===Baptist Church===\nKasauli [[Baptists|Baptist Church]] is a 1923 brick and wood building, situated close to the Sadar Bazzar. According to ''[[The Indian Express]]'' it is \"considered a unique example of colonial architecture of the British era\". In 2008 the church was damaged by a fire which destroyed all the internal furnishings.<ref name=\"ChurchesHimachalPradesh\" /><ref name=\"Kashyap\">Kashyap, Arvind; [http://www.indianexpress.com/news/kasauli-church-pastor-suspects-arson/385387/ \"Kasauli church pastor suspects arson\"]; ''[[The Indian Express]]'', 14 Nov 2008. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref><ref>[http://news.oneindia.in/2008/11/12/fire-breaks-out-in-kasauli-church-pastor-seeks-probe-1226497015.html \"Fire breaks out in Kasauli Church, Pastor seeks probe\"]; ''[[Oneindia.in]]'', 12 November 2008. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref>\n\n===Christ Church===\n[[File:Christ Church, Kasauli ,Solan ,Himachal Pardesh.jpg|alt=he church in itself is very beautiful and artistic. Attracts a lot of visitors.|thumb|picturesque structure ]]\nChrist Church was previously an [[Anglican]] church, inaugurated on 24 July 1853.<ref name=ChurchesHimachalPradesh>[http://himachal-pradesh-tourism.com/himachal-pradesh-churches.html \"Churches in Himachal Pradesh\"]; Himachal-pradesh-tourism.com. Retrieved 27 June 2012</ref>\n\nChrist church Kasauli came into existence in 1844 when Dr. Daniel Wilson (the great Metropolitan Bishop of Calcutta) appointed Rev MJ Jennings a chaplain to the new station Kasauli for the 1st time. Who started worship services in a barrack as there was no church building. \nAt the end of October 1844 Dr. Wilson, the Bishop of Calcutta paid his 1st visitation of Kasauli and on 26th of that month laid the foundation stone of future Christ Church. On 24th July 1853 the shed of the church was completed and on that day the church was used for the worship services for 1st time. \nIn 1880s the church tower was raised and the public clock was placed on it in the leadership of Rev J.B. Brunesson by importing the same from W.H. Bailey & Co of Manchester, England. The total cost of this was Rs. 2612 and 11 annas towards which Rs. 1250 was given by Government and the balance raised by public subscription. After remaining in hibernation for many decades this Tower Clock, In 2015 the clock starts ticking again with the wonderful efforts of Good Samaritan from Chandigarh and the Local EME workshop. Clock still works on Mechanical gears and now in Limca book of Records for being the oldest working Tower Turret Clock in India. [https://amolak.in/web/in-kasauli-the-church-clock-is-ticking-again/ Link for the restoration story]\n\n\n[[File:CHRIST CHURCH, KASAULI.JPG|270px|thumb|Christ Church, Kasauli]]\n\nSince 1970 it has been under the auspices of the [[Church of North India]] (CNI) in the diocese of [[Amritsar]].<ref name=KasauliChurches>[http://www.kasauliresort.com/kasauli_church.html Kasauli Churches] Kasauliresort.com. Retrieved 9 May 2011</ref> The church contains Spanish and Italian imported [[stained glass]] windows depicting [[Jesus|Christ]], [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Mary]], [[Barnabas|Saint Barnabas]] and [[Francis of Assisi|Saint Francis]].<ref name=Tribune/>\n\n===Circuit house===\n===Gurudwara Shri Guru Nanak Ji===\nThe [[Gurudwara]] ([[Sikh]] house of worship and hospitality) Shri Guru Nanak Ji is located in the Garkhal bazaar near Kasauli.<ref>[http://www.indiahimachalpradesh.com/kasauli/kasauli-gurudwara.html Kasauli Gurudwara] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323171529/http://www.indiahimachalpradesh.com/kasauli/kasauli-gurudwara.html |date=23 March 2012 }} indiahimachalpradesh.com. Retrieved 9 May 2011</ref> A further Sikh Gurudwara lies on the Kasauli-[[Mashobra]] (old [[Hindustan-Tibet Road|Hindustan-Tibet]]) Road near the Air Force Radar Station.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\n===Krishna Bhavan Mandir===\n'''Krishna Bhawan Mandir''', a [[Hindus|Hindu]] shrine, is located in the middle of the town. Dedicated to [[Krishna|Lord Krishna]], the temple exhibits blend of European and Indian architecture. The mandir is situated in the town and attracts tourists throughout the year. Krishna Bhawan Mandir was built in the year 1926 during the British regime. Imperial rulers, specialists of grand buildings came together with local craftsmen to construct this beautiful shrine. Keeping in mind the principles of Vastu Shastra, the designers and craftsmen built this religious monument.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n===Kasauli Brewery===\nThe [[Kasauli Brewery]] and distillery, founded in the 1820s{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} before the establishment of the Kasauli cantonment, is the oldest extant distillery for [[scotch whisky]] in Asia.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}} The Kasauli brewery is also known as [[Mohan Meakin]].{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n===Kasauli Club===\nThe Kasauli Club was established by civilians and service personnel in 1880, as the Kasauli Reading and Assembly Rooms. It gained its present name in 1898 when a limited liability company and constitution were established; its first director was Sir David Semple of Kasauli's Pasteur Institute. At the time the Club was for the exclusive use of the British Raj, and held social meetings, [[Tea dance|tea and dinner dances]], and [[Festival|galas]]. In 1915 regimental officers at [[Dagshai]], Solan and Subathu could be admitted as honorary members. At [[Indian Independence Act 1947|Independence]] in 1947, plans to sell the then loss-making Club failed.<ref name=Tribune2>Sharma, Ambika; [http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20050529/spectrum/main3.htm \"An exclusive retreat in the hills\"]; ''The Tribune'', Online edition, 29 May 2005. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref>\n\nThe Club was originally constructed of wood and plaster, and was typical of hill architecture. In 2001, after a 2000 restoration, it was destroyed by fire, losing \"elegant, old-world furniture, [and] precious and rare books\". By 2005 it had been redesigned and rebuilt in stone, and plans were put forward for a new attached gymnasium.<ref name=Tribune2/>\n\nIt is currently located within Indian Army premises and managed by a regular Indian Army Officer as Club Secretary, aided by civilian staff.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nIn April 2012 the Kasauli Club hosted a two-day [[Rhythm and Blues]] Festival as a [[benefit concert]] for ill children.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-09/india/31312385_1_army-band-army-jawan-music-lovers \"Rhythm and Blues festival ends with resolve to work for a cause\"], ''[[The Times of India]]'', 9 April 2012. Retrieved 7 July 2012</ref><ref name=Kapoor>Kapoor, Jaskiran; [http://www.indianexpress.com/news/music-in-the-mountains/930231/ \"Music in the Mountains\"]; ''The Indian Express'', 30 March 2012. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref>\n\n===Nahri Temple===\nThe Nahri Temple, devoted to the Goddess Durga and Lord Shiva, is thought to have been constructed around a hundred and fifty years ago. Also known as 'Jantar Mantar' and 'Choo Mantar Mahadev Temple', the temple is renowned for its festive celebration of Dushera and Shivratri. The temple boasts striking idols of the goddess Durga and Lord Shiva placed in the chamber of temple. Near this temple, there is century-old ''bauri'' which still offers sweet potable water. This temple is known to be visited by hundreds of pilgrims each year to present their prayers.\n\n===Hanuman Mandir (Monkey Point)===\n[[File:Fort of Beja Princely State ,Simla Hill States,Himachal Prades,India.jpg|thumb|Palace Fort Beja State]]Monkey Point is situated in the Air Force Station near the Lower Mall region about 4 km from the center of town. According to the Ramayana, when Lord Hanuman was returning from the Himalayas after acquiring the \"Sanjivani Booty\", one of his feet touched the hill; that's why the top of the hill is in the shape of a foot. On clear nights a view of [[Chandigarh]] can be seen from Monkey Point. \n\n===Beja State===\n{{Main article|Beja State}}[[Beja State]] was one of the 18 [[Hill States of India|Simla Hill States]], situated just below Kasauli to the west and bordered by Mahlog, Patiala, Kuthar and the Bharauli tract of Simla District around Sabathu. Beja included 45 villages, over an area of 13 km2 or 5 mi2 with 1,131 subjects.\n\n===Mahlog State===\n{{Main article|Mahlog }}\n[[File:View of Palace and fort of Mahlog State, under Simla Hill States ,Himachal Pradesh,India.jpg|thumb|View of Palace and fort of Mahlog State, under Simla Hill States]]The state of [[Mahlog]] was founded in 1183. Its original rulers were ruling earlier near [[Kalka]] when Mohamad Gauri attacked that area then they shifted to the Mahlog area. Initially 193 villages were in its jurisdiction but later over 300 villages were included. It was the one of the biggest Princely State of Simla Hill States under the British Raj.\n\n==Education==\nEducational institutions in or near Kasauli are the [[Lawrence School Sanawar]], The Pinegrove School, [[St. Mary's Convent School Kasauli|St. Mary's Convent School]], all co-educational, and the school at Kasauli's K.V. Air Force Station. These schools are affiliated with the [[Central Board of Secondary Education]]\nalso \n[[GSSS Kot Beja]] is a government senior secondary school at Kot beja near Kasauli .{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}[[File:Map of Mhlog State under Simla Hill States ,Himachal Pradesh,India.jpg|thumb|left|Map of Mhlog State under Simla Hill States, Himachal Pradesh, India]]\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- Anyone added here should have a Wikipedia article, or inline cites to Independent Verifiable Sources to prove notability and that they were born or spent significant time here - if none forthcoming, the name will be removed. Add in alphabetic order -->\n*[[Sir]] [[Braj Kumar Nehru]], former [[Governor]] of [[Assam]] and [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[Ambassador of India to United States of America|Ambassador of India to the United States]] (1961\u20131968) and [[India House, London|Indian High Commissioner to the United Kingdom]] (1973\u20131977) was a former resident.\n*[[Michael Baines]], English cricketer and British Army officer, born in Kasauli<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27613/27613.html |title=Player profile: Michael Baines |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2019-04-05 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n*[[Frank Blaker]], [[Victoria Cross]] recipient, born in Kasauli<ref>[http://www.victoriacross.org.uk/ggburma.htm \"Known graves of holders of The Victoria Cross - Frank Gerald Blaker\"], Victoriacross.org.uk. Retrieved 6 February 2014</ref>\n*[[Ruskin Bond]] &ndash; [[Anglo-Indian]] author, born in Kasauli\n*[[Tisca Chopra]], Indian film actress, born in Kasauli\n*[[Nathuram Godse]] &ndash; assassin of [[Mahatma Gandhi]], held in a Kasauli barrack during his trial<ref>Walia, Rajan; [http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-17/india/29427534_1_barrack-shimla-kasauli \"Museum planned in complex where Godse was jailed\"], ''The Times of India'', 17 April 2011. Retrieved 7 July 2012</ref>\n*[[Andy Mulligan (rugby union)|Andy Mulligan]] &ndash; [[Ireland national rugby union team|Irish rugby international]], born in Kasauli\n*[[Giles Radice, Baron Radice]] &ndash; resident of Kasauli, 1942&ndash;46<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2004-04-29/chandigarh/28345223_1_kasauli-amazing-memory-sanatorium \"Lord Radice on mission total recall\"], ''The Times of India'', 29 April 2004. Retrieved 7 July 2012</ref>\n*[[Khushwant Singh]] - part-time resident of Kasauli and inspiration for the annual Kushwant Singh Literary Festival hosted in Kasauli since 2012.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/chandigarh/writing-on-the-wall-8/\n| title = Writing on the Wall\n| date = 2013-10-15\n| website = The Indian Express\n| access-date = 2016-02-25\n}}</ref>\n*[https://vidwan.inflibnet.ac.in/profile/16780 Dr Krishan Kumar Tripathi]  - Pioneer Biotechnologist, worked as a scientist in CRI Kasauli.\n\n. Acharya '''Krishan Kant Attri''' (Born in Garkhal-Kasauli) - First Hindu Chaplain To UK Armed Force's. He Got MBE (Member of the Order of the British Empire) From Prince.\n\n. '''Ann Codrington''' (1894\u20131982) British Actress :\nBorn: September 10, 1894 in Kasauli, Solan, Himachal Pradesh, India\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Kasauli}}\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Kasauli}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110709163109/http://himachal.nic.in/welcome.asp Himachal Pradesh website]. Retrieved 8 July 2011\n*[http://www.himachal.nic.in/tcp/DPKASAULI.pdf \"Development plan for Kasauli Planning Area\"], Himachal Pradesh Government. Retrieved 8 July 2011\n*[http://www.tranquilblog.com/2013/07/kasaulitour.html \"Kasauli - My Ride\"], Tranquilblog\n*[http://eragenx.com/2016/07/11/things-to-do-places-visit-kasauli/ \"Places to visit in Kasauli\"], Travel Diary\n\n[[Category:1842 establishments in British India]]\n[[Category:Cantonments of British India]]\n[[Category:Cantonments of India]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Solan district]]\n[[Categor